<DOC><DOCNO> AP880730-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1850EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Ireland-Population     07-30 0134</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Ireland-Population,0138</SECOND><HEAD>Irish Population Drops For First Time In 27 Years</HEAD><DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ireland's population has dropped for thefirst time in 27 years because of mass emigration by young peopleseeking work abroad, the government's Central Statistics Officereported Saturday.   Ireland's population is estimated to be 3,538,000, or 5,000fewer people than in April 1987, the office said.   ``The reason for the net decline in population is emigration,''it said in a statement.   Ireland, beset by high taxes and 17 percent unemployment, hasexperienced its biggest wave of emigration since the 1920s. Anestimated 25,000 to 30,000 people leave each year.   The government estimates about 40,000 to 50,000 young Irish havegone to the United States in the past seven years in search ofbetter conditions, many as illegal aliens.</TEXT></DOC>